---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import KeyTakeaways from '../components/KeyTakeaways.astro';
import References from '../components/References.astro';
import RelatedPages from '../components/RelatedPages.astro';
import VariantCard from '../components/VariantCard.astro';
import PigmentSwitch from '../components/PigmentSwitch.astro';
import AppetiteCircuit from '../components/AppetiteCircuit.astro';
import { variantsByAxis, type Variant } from '../data/variants';

const skin = variantsByAxis('skin');
const metabolic = variantsByAxis('metabolic');

// One deduped, alphabetised bibliography across every variant shown. Cards cite
// inline; this is the formal reference list the rest of the site ends with.
const references = [];
const seen = new Set<string>();
for (const v of [...skin, ...metabolic] as Variant[]) {
  for (const s of v.sources) {
    if (!seen.has(s.url)) {
      seen.add(s.url);
      references.push(s);
    }
  }
}
references.sort((a, b) => a.authors.localeCompare(b.authors));
---

<PageLayout
  title="Genetics of the melanocortin system"
  kicker="Genetics"
  description="The pathway where skin and body-weight genetics turn out to be the same pathway — a research-grade reference to the variants in MC1R, MC4R, POMC and their partners, and what the literature associates with each."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'MC1R', type: 'Gene', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_1_receptor'] },
    { name: 'MC4R', type: 'Gene', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_4_receptor'] },
    { name: 'Proopiomelanocortin', type: 'Gene', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proopiomelanocortin'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'The melanocortin pathway is where "skin genes" and "obesity genes" overlap: MC1R tunes pigment and UV risk, while MC4R, POMC and LEPR set appetite and body weight.',
      'Some genes sit on both axes at once — biallelic POMC loss causes early obesity, adrenal insufficiency, and red hair simultaneously, because one precursor feeds all three receptor arms.',
      'Variants are not all vulnerabilities: MC4R I251L is a resilience allele associated with lower obesity risk, alongside the loss-of-function alleles that raise it.',
      'This is a population-level research reference, not a diagnostic tool. It reports what the literature associates with a variant — never a personal risk score.',
    ]}
  />

  <aside
    class="not-prose my-8 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--bg-elevated)] p-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--text-muted)]"
  >
    <p class="!mt-0">
      <strong class="font-medium text-[var(--text)]">Research-grade, not diagnostic.</strong>
      Each entry summarises published, population-level associations with strength-of-evidence
      noted. It cannot tell you what a variant means for you: penetrance varies, most traits are
      polygenic, and genotype interpretation belongs with a qualified genetic counsellor.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <p>
    Ask which genes shape the skin and which shape body weight, and you expect two
    different answers. In the melanocortin system you get one pathway. A single
    precursor — <a href="/system">pro-opiomelanocortin (POMC)</a> — is cut into the
    peptides that act on <a href="/receptors">five receptors</a>: the same α-MSH
    signal that drives pigment through <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a> in the skin
    drives satiety through <a href="/receptors/mc4r">MC4R</a> in the hypothalamus. So
    the genetics of sun sensitivity and the genetics of appetite run through
    neighbouring parts of one circuit — and a few genes sit squarely on both.
  </p>

  <p>
    The entries below are grouped by the axis each variant speaks to. Genuinely
    pleiotropic variants (tagged <span class="font-mono text-[0.8em]">Both axes</span>)
    appear under both headings on purpose.
  </p>

  <h2>Skin &amp; UV-risk axis</h2>
  <PigmentSwitch />
  <p>
    Pigmentation and photoprotection. MC1R is one of the most variable genes in the
    human genome; its loss-of-function "R" alleles bias melanocytes toward red/yellow
    pheomelanin and away from the eumelanin that shields DNA from UV — so the variants
    below are, in effect, different settings of the switch shown above.
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose mt-6 flex flex-col gap-4">
    {skin.map((v) => <VariantCard variant={v} />)}
  </div>

  <h2>Appetite &amp; body-weight axis</h2>
  <AppetiteCircuit />
  <p>
    The leptin–melanocortin circuit that sets energy balance. Loss-of-function
    variants here are the most common monogenic causes of severe early-onset obesity
    — and several respond to the MC4R-pathway agonist
    <a href="/setmelanotide">setmelanotide</a>. Resilience alleles that strengthen the
    satiety brake live on the same axis. Each variant below is a place the circuit
    above can break — or, for the protective alleles, hold firmer.
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose mt-6 flex flex-col gap-4">
    {metabolic.map((v) => <VariantCard variant={v} />)}
  </div>

  <h2>How to read the evidence tags</h2>
  <p>
    Every card carries a strength-of-evidence badge so a textbook variant is never
    mistaken for a single-cohort signal:
    <strong class="font-medium">Established</strong> (reproduced, mechanism understood,
    in clinical databases), <strong class="font-medium">Strong</strong> (multiple
    independent cohorts agree), <strong class="font-medium">Emerging</strong> (real but
    limited replication), and <strong class="font-medium">Contested</strong> (published
    both ways). Allele frequencies and identifiers are being verified against gnomAD,
    dbSNP, ClinVar and OMIM as entries are finalised.
  </p>

  <RelatedPages slug="genetics" />
  <References items={references} />
</PageLayout>
